              <tr valign="top"> 
                <td height="401" width="100%"><font color="#000000"> </font> <br>
                   <table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Rating Decks Using Decktech</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.GIF" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?deck=41"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Charles "huku" Taragin</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">This article considers Decktech's process for evaluating decks and provides a decision rule for deck evaluation.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">One of the best and worst features of this site is deck evaluation. Deck evaluation  not only allows decktech subscribers to post their own decks and recieve criticism for their efforts, but enables subscribers  to evaluate their fellows' decks. While I do firmly believe that deck creation and evaluation are integral parts of the game, Decktech's system does not neccessarily give 'winning' decks a high rating. In order to make this discussion clearer, consider the following scenario. John Doe constructs a deck that in his local playing environment loses only 1 in thirty times. However, when submitted to decktech, a subscriber doesn't like the deck (either because he didn't understand the decks strategy, did not like the deck's theme, or believed it had some other weakness) and gives it 2.5 stars. This rating is an obvious error, because it does not reflect the decks proven record. A 2.5 star rating would delegate this otherwise excellent strategy to the end of the deck list, where virtually no one on decktech would ever see it.<br>
<br>
In order to assuage this flaw in the rating system, I believe that no deck should be considered evaluated until it has recieved two ratings from two different individuals. Furthermore, no ratings should be posted until a deck has been rated twice. Since this system encourages multiple postings, decktech may not wish to rely upon a mean or average rating, but rather upon a different summary statistic, like the median (which tends to disregard extreme ratings) or the mode (which focuses on the most frequent rating).<br>
<br>
For deck reviewers, I would caution them to think critically about all elements of a deck, and not disregard <br>
a deck simply because it answered a problem in a different way. Also, decks should only be compared to the next best possible deck on the same side, and not on whether they can beat every strategy on the opposite side. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?deck=41"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?deck=41" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR> 
